[[Category:Concepts in the philosophy of science]]

'''Inclusive masculinity''' is an approach to thinking about [[masculinity]] in the context of social changes that have undermined traditional [[hegemonic masculinity]] and its associated [[homophobia]], which each have driven men to avoid certain behaviors in order to avoid being publicly perceived as gay; it holds that there are increasingly societal spaces in which men no longer need to behave in hypermasculine ways in order to be accepted. When this occurs, men can engage in a variety of previously feminine practices without the fear of being perceived gay or weak.<ref name=RobertsIntro>{{cite book|editor1-last=Roberts|editor1-first=Steven|title=Debating Modern Masculinities: Change, Continuity, Crisis?|date=2014|publisher=Springer, Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9781137394842|language=en|last=Roberts|first=Steven|chapter=Introduction}}</ref>{{rp|4, 8–9}}

The theory was published in 2009 by [[Eric Anderson (sociologist)|Eric Anderson]] in a book called "Inclusive Masculinity".<ref name=RobertsIntro/>{{rp|4}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Eric|title=Inclusive masculinity : the changing nature of masculinities|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=9780415804622|edition=Paperback}}</ref> and further elaborated by Mark McCormack in a 2012 book.<ref name=RobertsIntro/>{{rp|4}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=McCormack|first1=Mark|title=The declining significance of homophobia how teenage boys are redefining masculinity and heterosexuality|date=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199778485}}</ref>

It can be contrasted with views that of contemporary masculinity as being a crisis and in need of restoration.<ref name=RobertsIntro/>{{rp|4}}

